HuffPost Articles Dataset¶

This notebook explores Natural Language (NLP) Models for classifying article headlines and short descriptions of articles into a category set by the ffPost.

Note: Given that ETL and some of the models take long to run, the notebook saves this runs to disk so that later one can call the models and results and reconstruct graphs. Once all the notebook has run all completed one only requires to call cells in "Loading Libraries and Data" and the "Data Split" cell in "Models". Once these cells are run, then one can re-run the cells of each model and further explore its results.

Next, you will find the outline of the notebook so you can jump between different sections.

Outline¶

  1. Loading Libraries and Data
  2. ETL
  3. Models
    1. Naive Bayes (NB)
    2. Logistic Regression (LR)
    3. Random Forests (RF)
    4. Neural Networks (NN)
  4. Conclusions

First 7 categories sum up more than 50% of the articles. It is possible that differences between these categories could be very small.

Looking at the most common words by category, one can see that the difference between some categories could be really small. For example: "ARTS & CULTURE", "ARTS" and "CULTURE & ARTS" have large frequency in words like "art" y "artist". As well, we can see that the words "Trump" is common to many categories and not only "POLITICS". It is possible that using ngrams could be usefull for discrminating among categories.

text_clf_CV = Pipeline([('vect', CountVectorizer()),
                      ('tfidf', TfidfTransformer()),
                      ('clf', MultinomialNB()),
                    ])
param_grid = {
    'vect__max_features': [500,1000,5000,10000],
    'tfidf__use_idf': (True, False)
}

The most common confusions are:

  • Three most common categories get mixed up with the rest of categories.
  • "STYLE & BEAUTY" gets mixed up with "STYLE"
  • "FOOD & DRINKS" gets mixed up with"TASTE"
  • "POLITICS" gets mixed up with "BUSSINESS", "THE WORLDPOST", "ENTERTAIMENT"

Let's investigate some example of errors made by the model. First, let us look at articles which are in the "BUSINESS" category but where predicted as "POLITICS" by our model.

Instead of doing Cross-Validation on the training data, we are setting apart another set called validation set where we are going to be testing different parameters of the same model.

What we are seeing in these two graphs is the result of ElasticNet Logistic Regression (LR) at 3 different alpha levels:

  • Alpha equal to 0.0: It is the same as Ridge LR
  • Alpha equal to 1.0: It is the same as Lasso LR
  • Alpha equal to 0.5: It is the same as ElasticNet LR with equal weight to Ridge as to Lasso.

The 3 settings had similiar performance (around 58%). Anyway, Ridge LR took 0.045 hours (around 3 minutes) while ElasticNet and Lasso took 9.4 and 5.75 hours respectively.

Neural Networks (NN)¶

For neural networks models, the appoach is a bit different because it does not require the clean version of the data. This is due to the fact that Glove Embbeding is used so that the way the word is written matters.

Hyperparameter exploration for Neural networks change in method and data split. We are not going to be using cross-validation but a validation set set apart before hand. On the other hand, given the large number of parameters in neural networks, the search is going to be using Bayesian Optimization.

Let's dive in.

print("Applying GloVe vectors...")

embeddings_index = {}
f = open(glove_file_path, encoding="utf8")
for line in f:
    values = line.split()
    word = values[0]
    coefs = np.asarray(values[1:], dtype='float32')
    embeddings_index[word] = coefs
f.close()

print('Found %s word vectors.' % len(embeddings_index))

embedding_matrix = np.zeros((max_words, embedding_dim))
for word, i in word_index.items():
    if i < max_words:
        embedding_vector = embeddings_index.get(word)
        if embedding_vector is not None:
            embedding_matrix[i] = embedding_vector    
print("Applying GloVe vectors completed.")

In [34]:
print("Creating model structure...")

def baseline_model(optimizer='Adam', lr=0.001, hidden_layer_sizes=(256, 128, 64, ), dropout=0.0):
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Embedding(max_words, embedding_dim, input_length=max_sequence_len))
    model.add(Flatten())
    for hidden_layer_size in hidden_layer_sizes:
        model.add(Dense(hidden_layer_size, activation="relu"))
        model.add(Dropout(dropout))
    model.add(Dense(41, activation='softmax'))

    # fix the weights for the first layer to those provided by the embedding matrix
    model.layers[0].set_weights([embedding_matrix])
    model.layers[0].trainable = False

    if optimizer == 'RMSprop':
        opt = optimizers.RMSprop(lr=lr)
    elif optimizer == 'Adam':
        opt = optimizers.Adam(lr=lr)
        
    # Compile model
    model.compile(optimizer=opt,
                  loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                  metrics=['acc'])
    return model


# create model
keras_model = KerasClassifier(baseline_model)

batches = [16, 32, 64, 256, 512, 1024]
epochs = (2, 30)
lr = (1e-6, 1e-1, 'log-uniform')
dropout = (0.5, 0.8)
param_grid = dict(batch_size=batches, epochs=epochs, lr=lr, 
                  dropout=dropout)

print("Creating model structure completed.")

print("Creating model structure...")

def baseline_model_LSTM(optimizer='Adam', lr=0.001, dropout=0.0):
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Embedding(max_words, embedding_dim, input_length=max_sequence_len))
    # model.add(Dropout(dropout))
    model.add(Bidirectional(LSTM(embedding_dim)))
    model.add(Dense(41, activation='softmax'))

    # fix the weights for the first layer to those provided by the embedding matrix
    model.layers[0].set_weights([embedding_matrix])
    model.layers[0].trainable = False

    if optimizer == 'RMSprop':
        opt = optimizers.RMSprop(lr=lr)
    elif optimizer == 'Adam':
        opt = optimizers.Adam(lr=lr)
        
    # Compile model
    model.compile(optimizer=opt,
                  loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                  metrics=['acc'])
    return model

keras_model = KerasClassifier(baseline_model_LSTM, batch_size=1024, epochs=30)

def model_text_to_type(model_name):
    model_type = str(model_name)[-2:]
    return (model_type
                .replace('LR','Logistic Regression')
                .replace('NB','Naive Bayes')
                .replace('NN','Neural Networks')
                .replace('RF','Random Forests'))

It is interesting that among all models tested, the test accurarcy is better than the train accuracy. This could be due to the fact that Naive Bayes model is no complex enough to capture data variability and that the test is simply easier part of the dataset.

Three kinds of models have been tested:

  1. Naive Bayes Models (NB)
  2. Logistic Regression Models (LR)
  3. Random Forest (RF)
  4. Neural Networks Models (NN)

Naive Bayes (NB)¶

Naive Bayes models are models that are fast to fit with results that could give an idea of a baseline model. Given that they are fast to fit, it is easier to test with different variants:

  • headlines NB: This is the baseline variant of the baseline model with an accuracy of 50%
  • short description NB: The dataset has both headlines and short descriptions with headlines being more informative than short descriptions since only using this columns obtained an accuracy of 39%
  • headlines desription NB: This the model combines both columns. For instance, it can be seen that adding the description column to the headlines column give us around 2-3 percentual point improvement in accuracy.
  • headlines ngrams BN: it is interestintly to note that adding ngrams to Naive Bayes model did not improved accuracy much.
  • headlines description 7 categories NB: Naives Bayes model was tested reducing the categories from 41 to 8 with both "headlines" and "short description" columns. This model showed and improvement of around 18 percentual points in accuracy.

We could see two specific drawbacks of simple models such as Naive Bayes:

  1. It uses a list of most common words in the dictionary and increasing to large dictionaries tends to lead to poor results. Nevertheless, it is possible that words that are not so common could be highly discriminant among categories.
  2. It assumes that the order of words do not matter, which is not a very realisitc assumption.

Logistic Regression (LR)¶

With Logistic Regression models, we try to improve on the first Naive Bayes assumption explained above by using not just a subset of common words but by using all words in the dictionary and using strategies for automatic feature selection. In particular, two Logistic Regression variants have been tested:

  • headlines PCA LR: With PCA we are trying to find a subspace spanning a smaller dimension than the orginal space of features. This subspace is selected as the first "n_dim" that capture the largest varaibility of the original space. Nevertheless, it is not assured that this subspaces captures the features which are important for the current problem. In fact the model showed the lowest accuracy.
  • headlines elasticnet LR: This approach instead, tries to combine L1 and L2 regularization. On the one hand, L1 regularization (Lasso) tends to send many coefficients to zero resulting in a sparse representation where only those useful words for discrimination among categories get selected. L2 regularization (Ridge) on the other hand, tries to limit large values of coefficients. This approach resulted in an increase of around 9 percetual points with respect to Naive Bayes model that used the same data,
  • headlines description 7 categories LR: Naives Bayes model was tested reducing the categories from 41 to 8 with both "headlines" and "short description" columns. This model showed and improvement of around 6 percentual points in accuracy with respect to Naive Bayes model with the same data.

Random Forests (RF)¶

  • headlines RF: This a simple Random Forest Model on the headlines column. It had an accuracy of 52% which is a little better Naive Bayes model but not as good as other approaches such as LSTM and Logistic Regression. One important thing to notice with RF model is that, with a dataset as large as this one, the saved model is around 800MBs compared to toher models that are as small a 10MBs

Neural Networks (NN)¶

  • headlines NN: This is a dense vanilla version of neural networks with Bayesian Optimization for optimizing parameters. Unfortunately the neural network structured used did not improve even Naive Bayes model with an accurary of 46.8% with respect to a 50% accuracy of Naive Bayes.
  • headlines LSTM NN: Bidirectional LSTM Recurrent network. This network does not have hyperparameter optimization and it has an accuracy of around 55% in testing. This more complex model is able capture more than vanilla NN. The trainning score is 10 percetual points higher than the training one, which means that there is overfitting. This network with 30 epochs took arounf 4 hours to compute.
  • pytorch pretrained NN: This is the best model on headlines alone with an accuracy of 63%. This model was trained on Google Colab which has GPU backend. While the finetunning using CPU takes around 3 hours per epoch, on Google Colab only takes 3 minutes.
